							"createTime" : {
								"__type" : "time",
								"time" : {
									"__type" : "dateAndTime",
									"dateAndTimeString" : "2026-04-30T15:26:11.433919-04:00"
								}
							},
							"editEmail" : {
								"__type" : "email",
								"emailString" : "<unknown>"
							},
							"editTime" : {
								"__type" : "time",
								"time" : {
									"__type" : "dateAndTime",
									"dateAndTimeString" : "2026-04-30T15:44:19.670501-04:00"
								}
							},
							"uid" : {
								"__type" : "uid",
								"uidString" : "+GrlOhClQsu1UaRrUwKSrw=="
							},
							"paragraphStyle" : {
								"__type" : "textStyle"
							},
							"string" : "At an an application level, 'frames' and 'slots' are known to be build into the design of several application systems including: (1) JP Morgan's *Kapital System*, (2) Florida Power and LIght's *Power Billing System*, (3) some systems in Vancouver were developed by [Big Server Software](https://opengovca.com/vancouver-business/02-102192). \n\nSystems making heavy use of meta data that were similar to a frame and slot system were OOCL's container shipping system which was also used by NYK Lines, and HTS  in Toronto.\n\nIn converstion with *Marin Kraft*, one of the architects of the *Power Billing System*, slots are not a performance problem for most systems at an application level. He said the ICE (Inter-Contintental Excahnge) would not be suitable because of the performance requirements. They had even turned garbage collection off while trading was in progresss.\n\nIt is important to note that all of the systems described above were using GemStone by GemTalk Systems."
						}
					]
				},
